 In setting out a new agenda for the field, it makes an ambitious argument for the importance of writing histories which are present-centred and politically engaged. This means that the book engages head-on with ferocious debates about men's social position and the status of masculinity in contemporary public life. In establishing a critical genealogy for the proliferation of this crisis talk, it sets out new ways of understanding how men's lives and ideas of masculinity have changed over time while patriarchy and male power have persisted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aAyers, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuxton, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharnock, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelap, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoulbrook, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoulbrook, Matt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohansen, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Katie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKane-Galbraith, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMechen, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMechen, Ben, eeditor.4